						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="document" href="/en/Dossiers/Commodities/Other-commodities/Coffee/Relevant-publications/Biofertilizers-for-coffee-cultivation" title="Biofertilizers for coffee cultivation" alt="document">Biofertilizers for coffee cultivation</a></h2>

	
	
	
	
					<p> The potential of biofertilizers for coffee cultivation in India is discussed. The definition of biofertilizers, advantages of biofertilizers, and biofertilizer types and classification are discussed. There are 3 types: N-fixing biofertilizers, phosphate-mobilizing biofertilizers, and organic matter decomposers. These are discussed in some detail, with an indication of their scope in coffee cultivation. Recommendations for the application of biofertilizers are provided. <i>Indian Coffee (India),  v. 59(5) p. 3-8</i> </p>
							<p><span class="date">5/04/2006</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="document" href="/en/Dossiers/Commodities/Other-commodities/Coffee/Relevant-publications/Biofertilizers-for-coffee-cultivation">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="document" href="/en/Dossiers/Commodities/Other-commodities/Coffee/Relevant-publications/Micro-sprinkler-system-considered-a-viable-and-economical-technology-for-irrigation-of-robusta" title="Micro-sprinkler system considered a viable and economical technology for irrigation of robusta" alt="document">Micro-sprinkler system considered a viable and economical technology for irrigation of robusta</a></h2>

	
	
	
	
					<p> A comparative economic analysis of conventional sprinkler and micro-sprinkler irrigation systems for robusta coffee was carried out in Chikmagalur district of Karnataka, India, during the period 1996-2000. It was shown that the micro-sprinkler had a higher benefit cost ratio and a greater positive net present value than the conventional sprinkler system. The efficiency gain from the use of the micro-sprinkler with the sprinkler level of inputs (capital, fertilizer, and labour) was nearly 12%. Thus, the micro-sprinkler system was considered a viable and economical technology for the irrigation of robusta. The main constraints to the adoption of the system were the clogging problem of the micro-sprinklers and the need for skilled workers to ensure maintenance. From authors' summary. <i>Journal of Coffee Research (India), v. 30(1) p. 40-46</i> </p>
							<p><span class="date">5/04/2006</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="document" href="/en/Dossiers/Commodities/Other-commodities/Coffee/Relevant-publications/Micro-sprinkler-system-considered-a-viable-and-economical-technology-for-irrigation-of-robusta">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="document" href="/en/Dossiers/Commodities/Other-commodities/Coffee/Relevant-publications/Africa-Prospects-of-organic-coffee-production-in-Kenya-a-review" title="Africa: Prospects of organic coffee production in Kenya - a review" alt="document">Africa: Prospects of organic coffee production in Kenya - a review</a></h2>

	
	
	
	
					<p> Organic coffee, which is coffee produced without the use of inorganic fertilizers and pesticides, is commonly consumed in the developed countries. This type of coffee is usually sold at higher prices than ordinary coffee. Although Kenya produces high-quality coffee, it does not produce certified organic coffee. The possibilities of producing organic coffee in Kenya are discussed. From authors' summary. <i>Kenya Coffee (Kenya), v. 59(695) p. 1847-1849</i> </p>
							<p><span class="date">5/04/2006</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="document" href="/en/Dossiers/Commodities/Other-commodities/Coffee/Relevant-publications/Africa-Prospects-of-organic-coffee-production-in-Kenya-a-review">Read more...</a>
