						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="document" href="/en/Dossiers/Commodities/Other-commodities/Coffee/Relevant-publications/Developing-synthetic-coffee-seeds" title="Developing synthetic coffee seeds" alt="document">Developing synthetic coffee seeds</a></h2>

	
	
	
	
					<p> An encapsulation technique used for developing synthetic seeds of coffee is reported. Beads of encapsulated embryos or axillary buds were formed by pipetting these, mixed with 6% sodium alginate, into 2% CaCl2 solution. Plants could be successfully regenerated from the encapsulated zygotic and somatic embryos of both <i>Coffea arabica</i> and <i>Coffea canephora</i> cultivars. <i>Indian Coffee (India), v. 64(2) p. 3-5</i>   </p>
							<p><span class="date">5/04/2006</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="document" href="/en/Dossiers/Commodities/Other-commodities/Coffee/Relevant-publications/Developing-synthetic-coffee-seeds">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="document" href="/en/Dossiers/Commodities/Other-commodities/Coffee/Relevant-publications/Can-an-agricultural-commodity-be-de-commodified-and-if-so-who-is-to-gain" title="Can an agricultural &quot;commodity&quot; be de-commodified, and if so, who is to gain?" alt="document">Can an agricultural &quot;commodity&quot; be de-commodified, and if so, who is to gain?</a></h2>

	
	
	
	
					<p> For coffee beans, farm gate and world market prices are now at historically low levels. At the same time, though, global coffee consumers are becoming more discerning. With at least as much potential taste variety as in the case of wine, final product prices are becoming more differentiated. Margins for some coffees can therefore be expected to increase significantly as consumers become more discriminating in their tastes. Whilst the price spread is growing in global trading markets, it is simultaneously narrowing at the farm gate. At the same time, the destruction of coffee marketing boards (largely due to Structural Adjustment Programmes) has had unintended effects: instead of their margins accruing to farmers, almost all of these margins are being absorbed in the high-income importing countries. Thus, left to market forces, farmers would gain little from increasingly discriminating final consumer tastes. The global branders and the supermarket chains are more likely to appropriate these growing product rents. However, if consumers can be educated to recognize that better coffees are directly linked to their place of origin rather than to their brand names, a more equal global distribution of income is likely to emerge in this value chain. Several stakeholders may be involved in influencing final consumer preferences in an appropriate manner. <i>Discussion Paper Institute of Development Studies (UK), no. 380</i> </p>
							<p><span class="date">5/04/2006</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="document" href="/en/Dossiers/Commodities/Other-commodities/Coffee/Relevant-publications/Can-an-agricultural-commodity-be-de-commodified-and-if-so-who-is-to-gain">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="document" href="/en/Dossiers/Commodities/Other-commodities/Coffee/Relevant-publications/Regional-seminar-on-the-actual-situation-of-coffee-processing-review-and-technological-improvements-proceedings" title="Regional seminar on the actual situation of coffee processing: review and technological improvements - proceedings" alt="document">Regional seminar on the actual situation of coffee processing: review and technological improvements - proceedings</a></h2>

	
	
	
	
					<p> A seminar on coffee processing technology was held in Heredia, Costa Rica, in 1998. An overview of the current processing methods in Costa Rica, Dominican Republic, El Salvador, Guatemala, Honduras, Jamaica and Nicaragua was provided. Technological advances with regard to environmentally-sound processing methods, global trends in coffee marketing, and conceptual aspects of coffee quality were discussed. Special attention was paid to technical, environmental and quality aspects of waste management in the wet processing method: (1) the treatment of pulp; (2) using less water in pulping and washing; (3) filtering the effluent; (4) sedimentation; (5) anaerobic treatment; and (6) plant bed cleaning using water hyacinth or bull rush; (7) the composting of pulp using the Californian red earth worm; (8) pulping equipment; and (9) drying systems. <i>Serie de Ponencias, Resultados y Recomendaciones de Eventos Tecnicos (IICA/PROMECAFE)</i> </p>
							<p><span class="date">5/04/2006</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="document" href="/en/Dossiers/Commodities/Other-commodities/Coffee/Relevant-publications/Regional-seminar-on-the-actual-situation-of-coffee-processing-review-and-technological-improvements-proceedings">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="document" href="/en/Dossiers/Commodities/Other-commodities/Coffee/Relevant-publications/Latin-American-symposium-on-coffee-growing-proceedings" title="Latin-American symposium on coffee growing: proceedings" alt="document">Latin-American symposium on coffee growing: proceedings</a></h2>

	
	
	
	
					<p> In 2000, a symposium on coffee growing in Latin America was held in San Jose, Costa Rica. The themes were crop husbandry, plant nutrition, genetics and plant breeding, integrated pest management, post-harvest technology and quality control, and sustainability. Subjects included: (1) drip irrigation; (2) the emission of greenhouse gases in Costa Rica; (3) sources of Zn in coffee plantations in Costa Rica; (4) stability of hybrid progenies and backcrosses; (5) molecular marking and genetic diversity of Arabica coffee; (6) leaf area determination using regression models; (7) direct sowing of somatic embryos in a bioreactor; (8) biological aspects of the Uganda wasp ( <i>Prorops nasuta</i>); (9) biological control of the coffee berry borer ( <i>Hypothenemus hampei</i>) using the parasitoid <i>Phymastichus coffea</i>; (10) attractants of the coffee berry borer; (11) the enzyme trehalase in <i>Mycena citricolor</i>; (12) the causes of corchosis; (13) the use of Metarhizium in the control of the coffee leaf miner <i>Leucoptera coffeella</i>; (14) prevention and control of <i>Mycena citricolor</i>; (15) the damage caused by <i>Rosellinia sp</i>.; (16) measuring pollution of rivers by coffee wastes in Costa Rica; and (17) the effect of altitude and variety on the organoleptic qualities of coffee.</p>
							<p><span class="date">5/04/2006</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="document" href="/en/Dossiers/Commodities/Other-commodities/Coffee/Relevant-publications/Latin-American-symposium-on-coffee-growing-proceedings">Read more...</a>
</div>
