						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="document" href="/en/Dossiers/Commodities/Other-commodities/Coffee/Relevant-publications/The-Microeconomics-of-Household-Collection-of-Wild-Coffee-in-Ethiopia-Some-Policy-Implications-for-In-situ-Conservation-of-Coffea-arabica-Genetic-Diversity" title="The Microeconomics of Household Collection of Wild Coffee in Ethiopia: Some Policy Implications for In-situ Conservation of Coffea arabica Genetic Diversity" alt="document">The Microeconomics of Household Collection of Wild Coffee in Ethiopia: Some Policy Implications for In-situ Conservation of Coffea arabica Genetic Diversity</a></h2>

	
	
	
	
					<p> World-wide cultivated arabica coffee is a native plant to Ethiopian highlands. Its wild populations can still be found in the fragmented montane rainforests of the country. To halt degradation and loss of the forest coffee genetic resources, the Ethiopian Government has established in-situ conservation areas in the south and southwestern montane rain forest regions of the country. However, there are several thousands of people who have been and still are dependent on the wild coffee populations from these forests for direct consumption and/or market sales. Thus, policy makers need to consider the needs and economic options of the local people in the periphery, so as to create a win-win relationship between conservation and local agricultural development (From authors’ abstract). <a href="http://www.ucl.ac.uk/bioecon/4th_2003/abebaw.doc" target="_blank">Download document</a> </p>
							<p><span class="date">4/04/2006</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="document" href="/en/Dossiers/Commodities/Other-commodities/Coffee/Relevant-publications/The-Microeconomics-of-Household-Collection-of-Wild-Coffee-in-Ethiopia-Some-Policy-Implications-for-In-situ-Conservation-of-Coffea-arabica-Genetic-Diversity">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="document" href="/en/Dossiers/Commodities/Other-commodities/Coffee/Relevant-publications/Robbing-Coffee-s-Cradle-GM-coffee-and-its-threat-to-poor-farmers" title="Robbing Coffee’s Cradle - GM coffee and its threat to poor farmers" alt="document">Robbing Coffee’s Cradle - GM coffee and its threat to poor farmers</a></h2>

	
	
	
	
					<p> The coffee crop relied upon by more than 60 million people for all or part of their livelihood is under threat.The market for this most valuable agricultural commodity has been volatile and fragile for decades, overproduction is crippling the coffee market and driving prices to all-time lows. Now industrial applications of GM coffee are poised to fundamentally change coffee production at the risk of putting millions of smallholder growers out of business (from the introduction). <a href="http://www.globalexchange.org/campaigns/fairtrade/coffee/ActionAidMay2001.pdf" target="_blank">Download PDF</a> </p>
							<p><span class="date">4/04/2006</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="document" href="/en/Dossiers/Commodities/Other-commodities/Coffee/Relevant-publications/Robbing-Coffee-s-Cradle-GM-coffee-and-its-threat-to-poor-farmers">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="document" href="/en/Dossiers/Commodities/Other-commodities/Coffee/Relevant-publications/Why-an-initiative-for-a-global-coffee-research-partnership-Increasing-awareness-of-stakeholders-in-a-crisis-situation" title="Why an initiative for a global coffee research partnership? - Increasing awareness of stakeholders in a crisis situation" alt="document">Why an initiative for a global coffee research partnership? - Increasing awareness of stakeholders in a crisis situation</a></h2>

	
	
	
	
					<p> This paper pleas for a global research partnership. At a time when a crisis, political motivation and multiple proposals are combined, research has more than ever its full role to play in the coffee commodity chain. Indeed, shared access to objective information is essential in the strategies chosen by stakeholders, in State adoption of agricultural or sectoral policies, and for implementing effective all-round consultation. This is decisive for the future of the commodity chain. The complexity of the issues calls for varied approaches, very often of a multidisciplinary type, and requires work on several time scales - short, medium and long term - and geographical scales - local, regional and international. Whilst certain questions asked of research need to be dealt with on a local or regional scale, other aspects are of an amplitude and complexity that require a global approach and the involvement of several categories of stakeholders (taken from the paragraph dealing with the essential role of research). <a href="http://sia2003-conference.cirad.fr/pdf/initiative-coffee.pdf" target="_blank">Download PDF</a> </p>
							<p><span class="date">4/04/2006</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="document" href="/en/Dossiers/Commodities/Other-commodities/Coffee/Relevant-publications/Why-an-initiative-for-a-global-coffee-research-partnership-Increasing-awareness-of-stakeholders-in-a-crisis-situation">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="document" href="/en/Dossiers/Commodities/Other-commodities/Coffee/Relevant-publications/Research-Priorities-For-Coffee-In-The-New-Millenium" title="Research Priorities For Coffee In The New Millenium" alt="document">Research Priorities For Coffee In The New Millenium</a></h2>

	
	
	
	
					<p> Hitherto coffee research has been done in isolation by different countries. With in the country itself the Coffee Research Institutes often maintained isolation from mainstream basic research. On the other hand the consuming countries have strong research base in advanced areas such as  molecular techniques, quality evaluation, biological control etc. There is a strong felt need to integrate the research in producing and consuming countries for overall benefit of the coffee industry. The producing countries should adopt an open policy and freely exchange germplasm and forge collaborations with other countries for exchange of technical expertise and information. Common problems like coffee leaf rust, coffee berry borer, coffee berry disease and effluent disposal etc. needs to be addressed through multi-country collaborative research programmes. Likewise, transfer of technology through electronic media and farmers participatory method is the need of the hour to disseminate the research findings quickly in an effective manner. This approach alone would protect the interests of coffee producing countries in the present day liberalized, highly competitive global scenario (conclusion of the article). <a href="http://www.ico.org/event_pdfs/naidu.pdf" target="_blank">Download PDF</a> </p>
							<p><span class="date">4/04/2006</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="document" href="/en/Dossiers/Commodities/Other-commodities/Coffee/Relevant-publications/Research-Priorities-For-Coffee-In-The-New-Millenium">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="document" href="/en/Dossiers/Commodities/Other-commodities/Coffee/Relevant-publications/Towards-an-integrated-knowledge-systems-for-Smallholder-Coffee-Farmers" title="Towards an integrated knowledge systems for Smallholder Coffee Farmers" alt="document">Towards an integrated knowledge systems for Smallholder Coffee Farmers</a></h2>

	
	
	
	
					<p> Participatory research, farmers’ field schools, distance learning, telecentres, webbased knowledge, and similar schemes are the approaches that the authors believe need to tested, improved and then the most useful to become widely available to coffee farmers. Soft- and hardware have developed to the point where for the first time in history it is now possible to start linking all members of the coffee chain together at low cost, with information flowing freely in all directions. This is the aim for the coffee industry: to become a champion of diversity and transparency, to create a level playing field and a sense of global community for all those to whom coffee is a way of life. All the approaches outlined here are designed to empower farmers to choose their own future. <a href="http://www.ico.org/event_pdfs/baker.pdf" target="_blank">Download PDF</a> </p>
							<p><span class="date">4/04/2006</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="document" href="/en/Dossiers/Commodities/Other-commodities/Coffee/Relevant-publications/Towards-an-integrated-knowledge-systems-for-Smallholder-Coffee-Farmers">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
											</div> 	
	<br class="cl"/>
<p>

